## The AI mistake catalog

AI is remarkably good at generating React code that *looks* right. The structure is clean, the variable names are sensible, the JSX is well-formatted. But underneath that polished surface, the same mistakes appear over and over again. Once you know the catalog, you can spot them in seconds.

Let us walk through the eight most common AI React mistakes, from most frequent to least.

---

### Mistake #1: Derived state (the most common mistake)

This is the single most frequent mistake AI makes in React. AI loves to store values in state that should simply be calculated from other state.

**What AI generates:**

```tsx
const [items, setItems] = useState<Item[]>([]);
const [totalPrice, setTotalPrice] = useState(0);

useEffect(() => {
  const total = items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);
  setTotalPrice(total);
}, [items]);

return <p>Total: ${totalPrice}</p>;
```

**What it should be:**

```tsx
const [items, setItems] = useState<Item[]>([]);

const totalPrice = items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);

return <p>Total: ${totalPrice}</p>;
```

Why is the AI version wrong? The total price is *derived* from items. Every time items changes, React re-renders the component, and the calculation runs automatically. There is no need for a separate `useState` and `useEffect` — that adds complexity, an extra render cycle, and a potential for the total to be briefly out of sync with the items.

The rule is simple: **if a value can be calculated from existing state or props, calculate it directly. Do not store it in state.**

AI does this because it has seen thousands of examples of `useState + useEffect` patterns and defaults to them even when they are unnecessary.

---

### Mistake #2: Missing or wrong dependency arrays in useEffect

AI frequently gets the dependency array wrong — either omitting it entirely, leaving out dependencies, or including too many.

**What AI generates (missing dependency):**

```tsx
const [userId, setUserId] = useState("123");
const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

useEffect(() => {
  fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => setUser(data));
}, []); // Bug: userId is missing from the dependency array
```

**What it should be:**

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => setUser(data));
}, [userId]); // Correct: re-fetch when userId changes
```

With the empty `[]`, this effect runs once when the component mounts and never again — even when `userId` changes. The user sees stale data. With `[userId]`, the effect re-runs whenever the user ID changes, keeping the data fresh.

**What AI generates (no dependency array at all):**

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  console.log("User updated:", user);
}); // Bug: runs on EVERY render
```

Without a dependency array, this effect runs after every single render. If this were a fetch call, it would create an infinite loop: fetch -> set state -> re-render -> fetch -> set state -> re-render...

---

### Mistake #3: Missing error and loading states

AI often generates data-fetching code that handles only the happy path.

**What AI generates:**

```tsx
const [users, setUsers] = useState<User[]>([]);

useEffect(() => {
  fetch("/api/users")
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => setUsers(data));
}, []);

return (
  <ul>
    {users.map(user => (
      <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
    ))}
  </ul>
);
```

**What it should be:**

```tsx
const [users, setUsers] = useState<User[]>([]);
const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(true);
const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

useEffect(() => {
  fetch("/api/users")
    .then(res => {
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error("Failed to fetch users");
      return res.json();
    })
    .then(data => setUsers(data))
    .catch(err => setError(err.message))
    .finally(() => setIsLoading(false));
}, []);

if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
if (error) return <p>Error: {error}</p>;

return (
  <ul>
    {users.map(user => (
      <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
    ))}
  </ul>
);
```

The AI version shows nothing while the data loads (just an empty list), and if the API fails, the user sees... nothing. No feedback at all. The corrected version shows a loading indicator while waiting, displays an error message if something goes wrong, and checks the response status.

---

### Mistake #4: Missing or bad key props in lists

AI sometimes forgets the `key` prop entirely, or uses the array index as the key.

**What AI generates (index as key):**

```tsx
{items.map((item, index) => (
  <TodoItem key={index} item={item} />
))}
```

**What it should be:**

```tsx
{items.map(item => (
  <TodoItem key={item.id} item={item} />
))}
```

Using the index as a key causes problems when items are reordered, added, or removed from the middle of the list. React uses keys to track which item is which — if you reorder items but the keys stay 0, 1, 2, 3, React gets confused and may show wrong data in the wrong row. Always use a unique, stable identifier like an `id` field.

---

### Mistake #5: Missing preventDefault in form handlers

AI frequently forgets that HTML forms submit and reload the page by default.

**What AI generates:**

```tsx
const handleSubmit = () => {
  // process form data...
  submitData(formData);
};

return (
  <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
    {/* form fields */}
    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
  </form>
);
```

**What it should be:**

```tsx
const handleSubmit = (e: React.FormEvent) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  submitData(formData);
};
```

Without `e.preventDefault()`, clicking the submit button causes a full page reload — the browser's default form behavior. In a React single-page app, this wipes out all state and essentially resets the application. The form *appears* to do nothing because the page reloads before the JavaScript can process the data.

---

### Mistake #6: Overengineering

AI loves abstraction. Ask it for a simple component and it might give you a custom hook, a context provider, a utility function, and three helper components.

**What AI generates:**

```tsx
// useToggle.ts
const useToggle = (initialValue = false) => {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(initialValue);
  const toggle = useCallback(() => setValue(v => !v), []);
  const setTrue = useCallback(() => setValue(true), []);
  const setFalse = useCallback(() => setValue(false), []);
  return { value, toggle, setTrue, setFalse };
};

// In the component
const { value: isOpen, toggle: toggleMenu } = useToggle(false);
```

**What it should be:**

```tsx
const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);

<button onClick={() => setIsOpen(!isOpen)}>Menu</button>
```

The AI created an entire custom hook with `useCallback` optimizations for something that is a single `useState` and one line of toggle logic. This is not inherently broken, but it makes the code harder to read and maintain for no practical benefit. When reviewing AI code, ask: "Is this complexity earning its keep?"

---

### Mistake #7: Missing accessibility

AI rarely adds accessibility features unless you specifically ask.

**What AI generates:**

```tsx
<div onClick={handleClick} className="button">
  Close
</div>
```

**What it should be:**

```tsx
<button onClick={handleClick} aria-label="Close dialog">
  Close
</button>
```

The AI used a `<div>` styled to look like a button instead of an actual `<button>` element. A `<div>` cannot be reached by keyboard (Tab key), does not respond to Enter or Space, and is not announced as a button by screen readers. Always use semantic HTML elements — `<button>` for buttons, `<a>` for links, `<input>` for form fields.

Other common accessibility gaps: missing `alt` text on images, missing `aria-label` on icon-only buttons, no keyboard event handlers on custom interactive elements, missing form labels.

---

### Mistake #8: Stale closures in event handlers and timeouts

This is a subtle bug that AI creates when combining event handlers or timeouts with state.

**What AI generates:**

```tsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

const handleClick = () => {
  setTimeout(() => {
    setCount(count + 1); // Bug: uses stale count value
  }, 3000);
};
```

**What it should be:**

```tsx
const handleClick = () => {
  setTimeout(() => {
    setCount(prev => prev + 1); // Correct: uses updater function
  }, 3000);
};
```

The problem: when the timeout fires three seconds later, it uses the value of `count` from when the click happened, not the current value. If the user clicked three times quickly, each timeout sees `count` as 0 and sets it to 1 — so instead of counting to 3, it gets stuck at 1. The updater function `prev => prev + 1` always uses the most recent value.

---

### The pattern to notice

All eight mistakes share a common trait: **the code looks correct at first glance.** It compiles, it renders, and in simple test cases it might even work. The bugs appear in real usage — when data changes, when APIs fail, when users interact in unexpected ways, when someone navigates with a keyboard.

This is why reading React code is so valuable. You cannot catch these mistakes by looking at the screen. You catch them by reading the code.

